Yep, I think people were just having issues with the guestwifi dropping out - NAT works without any mucking around.

Re the proxy I didn't have to set it, VirtualBox seems to handle it natively. What I had to set was the NAT to allow SSH from my host to the VM (redirecting port 22 to 22 then ssh from the jost to 127.0.1.1)
<@UKB6FA1V0> has joined the channel

Also - I didn't get a chance to play with my machine - but saw some folk couldn't access the internet from their guest (but could from their host)
Suspect we might need to set proxy settings inside the guest? Will test in the office...
In Windows -  open a command prompt and type "netsh winhttp show proxy" to show the proxy details
and in a shell in your Linux guest - "export http_proxy = AAA.BBB.CCC.DDD" ( where this value is derived from the output above )
That's assuming people set it :slightly_smiling_face:
Hope every one remembers their BIOS password..
Also - re MacOS users, I'm told by a couple of folks - that the latest version of virtualbox doesn't work (6.0.8) - due to some driver signing changes. So I'll grab / download some older versions...
Task Manager on Windows 10 will tell you if you need to go into the BIOS. Towards the bottom right it says "Virtualisation: Enabled" (which is what we need).

Some folks only had 32 bit options in Virtualbox today - this means either need to disable HyperV and/or change Bios Settings to enable Virtualisation Support

<https://support.bluestacks.com/hc/en-us/articles/115004254383-How-do-I-disable-Hyper-V-on-Windows->
